snippet.textDisplay: Actually my "New year's resolution", if it can even be called that, is going well. I've set myself a weekly goal for 2020 and thus far am hitting it consistently, and have grown a lot in the area I chose. I think that's the result of working on my ability to set and meet good goals and challenges, though, which is a sort of skill in itself. That's an interesting thought actually, training yourself to be able to make a good goal and reach it is just as important as any other goal. Learning to work on something consistently and keep yourself motivated will help you to achieve every other goal you set out for yourself in the future.

snippet.textDisplay:
So... the Secret, but being more aware of the psychology.
An (slight) alternative I've found that works is to set a date in the future for (what I use) the zombie apocalypse. I need to prepare for the zombie apocalypse (which begins on 1st July). What do I need to do for that? Learn to drive, learn to cook, learn to dance. It's all applicable (Yes dance, you've see Thriller!). One year I picked up a martial art. Seven years later, (black belt) 2nd Dan.
On the level of gamification, if you have a group preparing for the zombie apocalypse, it can become gentle (but effective) encouragement to ask what your survivors have done this week, while threatening them with being ousted from the camp which will never exist.

snippet.textDisplay:
New Year's resolutions do not work, that's true. This is a method I can see working. Another method, the one I use, is taking the general theme of self-improvement, cutting it up into lots of sub-categories (skills, health, appearance, resume, home, social life, general satisfaction, education, social structure, power, networking, fiscal stability and many more). I then try and choose my activities based on if they help me improve those categories, how many they help improve and how much they improve them, along with the general practicality of doing the activities. They also have to be self-motivating in some way, either by social pressure (doing it in a club), having deadlines (such as in uni or a job) or just by being interesting or fun. I can then switch activities based on time passing, reached goals or a shift in interest.


Some categories have certain priority, of course, namely the ones that decline if they are neglected into a state with bad consequences. Fiscal stability, health, social life and home spring to mind.

snippet.textDisplay: I would like to personally recommend Scott Adams' book 'How to Fail at Everything and Still Win Big' and his systems-based method of self-improvement. Much like what is suggested in this video, he is very much against setting goals. He instead sees more success in honing in on the specific changes one can go about to reach their desired outcome. If you're trying to lose weight, don't say 'I want to lose x pounds in y days'. Say 'i'm going to make sure my fridge is stocked with ready-to-eat vegetables so it is harder to eat poorly out of convenience' and 'I'm going to take the stairs instead of the elevator every day' and 'i'm going to drink my daily coffee without creamer' and so on.

snippet.textDisplay:
I tend to keep any resolutions relaxed but very specific and have specific things in mind to help them along. Instead of “I’m losing the extra weight, no matter what!” Something like, “I want to lose weight mainly by increasing my exercise by walking every day, at least five minutes a day, and cutting out soda when possible.”

Telling myself I only have to do a tiny bit gets me in the headspace to show up, and that’s half the battle. I also don’t load on like ten things at once, but roll out my idea slowly as I can shoulder the added steps, so I don’t burn out.

This year I wanted to stop feeling so powerless to help causes I support by helping in new ways. I’m ill, so I can’t go out and volunteer time. I’m ill in the US, so I can’t stay home and volunteer a lot of money. But! I do have time and a little money. So I’m learning to knit. The cancer center my mom goes to can always use more hats. The women’s shelter needs baby clothes and blankets. Homeless shelters need winter wear of all kinds and blankets. So far I’ve learned the knit stitch, how to purl, and have started stockinette stitch, which is what most hats and sweaters use, and I’m working on a scarf. I’m not saving the world, and I wish I could do more. But, like, someone is going to go to bed less cold, because I learned how to move my hands a certain way to make fabric. It’s like alchemy. And that’s not nothing.
